recent_articles.title: Apple eyes US F1 rights, as Brad Pitt's race movie wins fans: FT
recent_articles.summary:
STORY: Call it the Brad Pitt effect.

The star’s "Formula 1: The Movie" is roaring through the box office.

It racked up $293 million in sales over its first ten days, according to Variety.

And the box office hit, made by Apple, could have ramifications in the real world of F1.

The Financial Times says iPhone maker is aiming to get the U.S. broadcast rights for the race series following the success of the film.

The rights will become available next year, and the report says Apple is challenging current holder ESPN, a unit of Disney.

Earlier in the year, several media outlets said Netflix was likely to be another contender.

Its series “Formula 1: Drive to Survive” helped boost the popularity of the sport in the U.S.

Reuters wasn’t immediately able to confirm the FT report, and there was no comment from Apple or F1.
